    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the confusion earlier; I will stop using the goblin metaphors immediately and focus strictly on the technical cybersecurity details you requested.\n\nHere is how a sysadmin would actually set up the Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) for a development team in a real-world scenario:\n\n1.  **Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) Configuration**:\n    The sysadmin defines specific roles within the Identity and Access Management (IAM) system, such as \"Junior Developer,\" \"Senior Developer,\" and \"DevOps Engineer.\" Each role is assigned a strict set of permissions. A Junior Developer might have read/write access to their own code repository and the ability to run local tests, but absolutely no access to production servers, database schema changes, or network configuration settings.\n\n2.  **Service Account Isolation**:\n    Instead of having developers log in with their personal credentials to access all systems, the sysadmin creates unique service accounts for CI/CD pipelines and application servers. These service accounts are granted only the specific permissions required for the application to function (e.g., writing to a staging database), preventing a compromised developer account from being used to pivot to other systems.\n\n3.  **Principle of Least Privilege",
      "source": "target",
